This file uses data from the FiveThirtyEight repository to isolate an individual pollster and their most recent polls at the time of every election in the dataset for the indicated years.

#Establish which pollster you wish to analyze:
pollsterOfChoice="Mitchell Research & Communications"
#Establish which years you wish to use data from (between 1998 and 2020):
earlyYear=1998
lateYear=2020

All Polls

After exploring the data with only the most recent polls before every election, we can compare these findings to data that includes all polls. What is the difference between their error? Their bias? Their predictive power?

The plot and summary statistics for margin of error from all polls conducted by Mitchell Research & Communications between 1998 and 2020 is shown below.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   0.130   2.640   5.120   7.286   8.588  38.420

The plot and summary statistics for bias towards republican candidates for all polls conducted by Mitchell Research & Communications between 1998 and 2020 is shown below.

##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  -7.570  -2.440   0.490   1.362   5.220  12.720

The mean bias for every year is displayed in the table and graph below.

For Mitchell Research & Communications the standard deviation of averaged yearly biases is 5.1354329.

Additionally, using just the most recent poll from each election predicted more races correctly than using all polls. Mitchell Research & Communications correctly predicted 66.6666667% of races using all polls from every election polled from 1998 to 2020.
